<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,1437,151,539]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,439,464]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[341,553,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Nothybidae" genus="Nothybus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="procerus">
<emphasis box="[341,553,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Nothybus procerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[681,787,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Nothybidae" genus="Nothybus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[681,787,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">Nothybus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1040,1101,439,464]" name="India" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">India</collectingCountry>
. Compared to other species in the 
<taxonomicName box="[195,298,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Nothybidae" genus="Nothybus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kempi">
<emphasis box="[195,298,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="28">N. kempi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, it has a relatively large glossy facial spot, a small faded cloud on CuA 
<number box="[1215,1223,490,504]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="1.0">1</number>
close to r-m, pale tergites 
<number box="[239,253,515,539]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="3.0">3</number>
and 
<number box="[307,323,514,539]" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" value="5.0">5</number>
, an entirely pale pleuron, a very high and narrow surstylus, and a phallus that is apically distinctive.
</paragraph>
